cs.PL, cs.AI, cs.LO, cs.DS, cs.SE 

This paper is about B-Prolog, which is a high-performance implementation of the standard Prolog language with several extensions including finite-domain constraint solving, arrays and hash tables, declarative loop constructs, and tabling. These features are commonly associated with programming languages and artificial intelligence, which suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the cs.PL and cs.AI sub-categories. Additionally, the paper discusses the TOAM Jr. architecture, which is a novel architecture for implementing Prolog systems. This suggests that the paper may also belong to the cs.LO (logic in computer science) and cs.SE (software engineering) sub-categories. Finally, the paper may also belong to the cs.DS (data structures and algorithms) sub-category, as it discusses the use of hash tables in B-Prolog.
